{"title_page": "Arturo Goetz", "text_new": "'''Arturo L. Goetz''' (24 June 1944 \u2013 28 July 2014) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] film [[actor]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Muri\u00f3 el actor Arturo Goetz|url=http://www.clarin.com/extrashow/arturo_Goetz-muerte_0_1183082191.html|accessdate=29 July 2014|publisher=Clar\u00edn|date=28 July 2014}}</ref> He worked in the [[cinema of Argentina]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0324496/ Arturo Goetz] at the [[Internet Movie Database]].</ref>\n\nHe studied for a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in economics at [[Jesus College, Oxford]], from 1971 to 1974, and published his findings on Argentine industrialization in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://de.ides.org.ar/desarrollo-economico-no-60/ |title=Desarrollo Econ\u00f3mico N\u00ba 60 &#124; Desarrollo Econ\u00f3mico |publisher=De.ides.org.ar |date= |accessdate=2014-07-30}}</ref> Whilst at Jesus College, he played [[football (soccer)|football]] for the college team and [[polo]] for the [[Oxford University|university]] team. After leaving Oxford, he worked as an economist at the United Nations in Geneva, and then at the Food and Agriculture Organization in Rome, where he worked on [[food security]] and South-South cooperation.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Beyond the slogan of South-South co-operation  |date=1981-06-30 |doi=10.1016/0305-750X(81)90007-3 |volume=9 |issue=6 |journal=World Development |pages=583\u2013585|last1=Goetz |first1=Arturol. }}</ref> He returned to Argentina in 1982 and established a treaty for South-South cooperation on food security for Latin America (Comite de Acci\u00f3n sobre Seguridad Alimentaria Regional, CASAR)<ref>La seguridad alimentaria: un desafio para Am\u00e9rica latina: http://www.nuso.org/upload/articulos/1038_1.pdf</ref> as well as the non-profit Fundaci\u00f3n CREAR, promoting development projects in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crearnet.org.ar/quienes-somos/nuestra-historia |title=Nuestra Historia |accessdate=July 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701225714/http://crearnet.org.ar/quienes-somos/nuestra-historia |archivedate=July 1, 2014 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=August 2019}} He took formal acting lessons after turning 50, having previously acted as an amateur.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Jesus College Newsletter|page=3|title=A postcard from: Argentina| last=Goetz|first=Arturo|publisher=[[Jesus College, Oxford]]|year=2008}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[C\u00f3mplices]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[El Amateur]]'' (1999) aka ''The Amateur''\n* ''[[El Camino (2000 film)|El Camino]]'' (2000) aka ''The Road''\n* ''[[Plan (film)|Plan]]'' (2000) \n* ''[[Four Aims and Flyin' Shoes]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Cama adentro]]'' (2004) aka ''Live-In Maid'' \n* ''[[The Holy Girl]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Derecho de familia]]'' (2006) aka ''Family Law'' \n* ''[[La Novia errante]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Other (2007 film)|The Other]]'' (2007) aka ''El Otro'' \n* ''[[El asaltante]]'' (2007) aka \"The mugger\"\n* ''[[El nido vacio]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[La sangre brota]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Rompecabezas]]'' (2010)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cinenacional name|id=arturo-goetz|old_id=12848|name=Arturo Goetz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goetz, Arturo}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Argentine male film actors]]\n[[Category:Argentine economists]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n\n{{Argentina-film-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Arturo L. Goetz''' (24 June 1944 \u2013 28 July 2014) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] film [[actor]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Muri\u00f3 el actor Arturo Goetz|url=http://www.clarin.com/extrashow/arturo_Goetz-muerte_0_1183082191.html|accessdate=29 July 2014|publisher=Clar\u00edn|date=28 July 2014}}</ref> He worked in the [[cinema of Argentina]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0324496/ Arturo Goetz] at the [[Internet Movie Database]].</ref>\n\nHe studied for a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in economics at [[Jesus College, Oxford]], from 1971 to 1974, and published his findings on Argentine industrialization in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://de.ides.org.ar/desarrollo-economico-no-60/ |title=Desarrollo Econ\u00f3mico N\u00ba 60 &#124; Desarrollo Econ\u00f3mico |publisher=De.ides.org.ar |date= |accessdate=2014-07-30}}</ref> Whilst at Jesus College, he played [[football (soccer)|football]] for the college team and [[polo]] for the [[Oxford University|university]] team. After leaving Oxford, he worked as an economist at the United Nations in Geneva, and then at the Food and Agriculture Organization in Rome, where he worked on [[food security]] and South-South cooperation.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Beyond the slogan of South-South co-operation  |date=1981-06-30 |doi=10.1016/0305-750X(81)90007-3 |volume=9 |issue=6 |journal=World Development |pages=583\u2013585|last1=Goetz |first1=Arturol. }}</ref> He returned to Argentina in 1982 and established a treaty for South-South cooperation on food security for Latin America (Comite de Acci\u00f3n sobre Seguridad Alimentaria Regional, CASAR)<ref>La seguridad alimentaria: un desafio para Am\u00e9rica latina: http://www.nuso.org/upload/articulos/1038_1.pdf</ref> as well as the non-profit Fundaci\u00f3n CREAR, promoting development projects in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crearnet.org.ar/quienes-somos/nuestra-historia |title=Nuestra Historia |accessdate=July 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701225714/http://crearnet.org.ar/quienes-somos/nuestra-historia |archivedate=July 1, 2014 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=August 2019}} He took formal acting lessons after turning 50, having previously acted as an amateur.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Jesus College Newsletter|page=3|title=A postcard from: Argentina| last=Goetz|first=Arturo|publisher=[[Jesus College, Oxford]]|year=2008}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[C\u00f3mplices]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[El Amateur]]'' (1999) aka ''The Amateur''\n* ''[[El Camino (2000 film)|El Camino]]'' (2000) aka ''The Road''\n* ''[[Plan (film)|Plan]]'' (2000) \n* ''[[Four Aims and Flyin' Shoes]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Cama adentro]]'' (2004) aka ''Live-In Maid'' \n* ''[[The Holy Girl]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Derecho de familia]]'' (2006) aka ''Family Law'' \n* ''[[La Novia errante]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Other (2007 film)|The Other]]'' (2007) aka ''El Otro'' \n* ''[[El asaltante]]'' (2007) aka \"The mugger\"\n* ''[[El nido vacio]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[La sangre brota]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Rompecabezas]]'' (2010)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cinenacional name|id=arturo-goetz|old_id=12848|name=Arturo Goetz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goetz, Arturo}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Argentine male film actors]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Argentine economists]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-film-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:more accurate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arturo_Goetz"}
{"title_page": "Marc Girardin", "text_new": "{{short description|French writer and politician}}\n[[Image:Girardin.jpg|thumb|right|Marc Girardin]]\n'''Saint-Marc Girardin''' (22 February 1801 \u2013 1 April 1873) was a French politician and [[Intellectual|man of letters]], whose real name was '''Marc Girardin'''.\n\n==Biography==\nGirardin was born in Paris. After a brilliant university career in the city, he began in 1828 to contribute to the ''[[Journal des D\u00e9bats]]'', on the staff of which he remained for nearly half a century. After the [[July Revolution]] and the accession of [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis Philippe]] as ''[[List of French monarchs|King of the French]]'' (the [[Liberalism and radicalism in France|liberal]] ''[[July Monarchy]]''), he was appointed professor of history at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and ''master of requests'' in the [[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]. Soon afterwards he exchanged his chair of history for one of poetry, continuing to contribute political articles to the ''Journal des D\u00e9bats'', and sitting as deputy in the Chamber from 1835 to 1848.\n\nIn 1833, he was charged with a mission to study [[German Confederation|German]] [[Education in Germany|methods of education]], and issued a report advocating the necessity of newer methods and of technical instruction. In 1844 he was elected a member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise|French Academy]].\n\nDuring the [[Revolutions of 1848 in France|Revolution of February 1848]] Girardin was for a moment a minister, but after the establishment of the [[Second French Republic]], he was not re-elected deputy in the [[French National Assembly|National Assembly]].\n\nAfter the [[Franco-Prussian War]], he was returned to the [[Bordeaux]] assembly by his old ''[[D\u00e9partement in France|d\u00e9partement]]'' &mdash; [[Haute-Vienne]]. His [[Orl\u00e9anist]] tendencies and his objections to the [[Third French Republic|Third Republic]] were strong, and although he at first supported [[Adolphe Thiers]], he afterwards became a leader of the opposition to the [[President of the French Republic|president]]. He died, however, in 1873 at [[Morsang-sur-Seine]], before Theirs was actually driven from power.\n\n==Works==\nHis chief work is his ''Cours de litt\u00e9rature dramatique'' (1843\u20131863), a series of lectures better described by its second title ''De l'usage des passions dans le drame''. The author examined dramatic passions, discussing the mode in which they are treated in ancient and modern drama, poetry and romance. The book, a defence of the ancients against the moderns, \"did not\", according to the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition]]'', \"take into account the fact that only the best of ancient literature has come down to us.\" Girardin's ''oeuvre'' was, overall, very hostile toward [[Romanticism]].\n\nGirardin's other works included ''Essais de litt\u00e9rature'' (2 vols., 1844), made up chiefly of contributions to the ''D\u00e9bats'', his ''Notices sur l'Allemagne'' (1834), and many volumes of collected ''Souvenirs'', ''R\u00e9flexions'', etc., on foreign countries and passing events (including his notes on the [[Regulamentul Organic|period of Russian administration]] in the [[Danubian Principalities]]). His last major works were ''[[Jean de La Fontaine|La Fontaine]] et les Fabulistes'' (1867) and an ''\u00c9tude sur [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau|J.-J. Rousseau]]'' (1870) which had appeared in the ''[[Revue des deux mondes]]''.\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Saint-Marc Girardin|volume=24|page=29}} ''In turn, it cites as references:''\n**Flatzfield and Meunier, ''Les Critiques litt\u00e9raires du XIXe si\u00e8cle'' (1894)\n**Ch. Labitte, ''Saint-Marc Girardin'', in the ''Revue des deux mondes'' (Feb. 1845)\n**Tamisier, ''Saint-Marc Girardin; \u00e9tude litt\u00e9raire'' (1876)\n\n{{Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise Seat 23}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girardin, Marc}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:French historians]]\n[[Category:French literary critics]]\n[[Category:French memoirists]]\n[[Category:French people of the Revolutions of 1848]]\n[[Category:19th-century French politicians]]\n[[Category:French travel writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:19th-century French journalists]]\n[[Category:French male journalists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century historians]]\n[[Category:19th-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century French male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French writer and politician}}\n[[Image:Girardin.jpg|thumb|right|Marc Girardin]]\n'''Saint-Marc Girardin''' (22 February 1801 \u2013 1 April 1873) was a French politician and [[Intellectual|man of letters]], whose real name was '''Marc Girardin'''.\n\n==Biography==\nGirardin was born in Paris. After a brilliant university career in the city, he began in 1828 to contribute to the ''[[Journal des D\u00e9bats]]'', on the staff of which he remained for nearly half a century. After the [[July Revolution]] and the accession of [[Louis-Philippe of France|Louis Philippe]] as ''[[List of French monarchs|King of the French]]'' (the [[Liberalism and radicalism in France|liberal]] ''[[July Monarchy]]''), he was appointed professor of history at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and ''master of requests'' in the [[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]. Soon afterwards he exchanged his chair of history for one of poetry, continuing to contribute political articles to the ''Journal des D\u00e9bats'', and sitting as deputy in the Chamber from 1835 to 1848.\n\nIn 1833, he was charged with a mission to study [[German Confederation|German]] [[Education in Germany|methods of education]], and issued a report advocating the necessity of newer methods and of technical instruction. In 1844 he was elected a member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise|French Academy]].\n\nDuring the [[Revolutions of 1848 in France|Revolution of February 1848]] Girardin was for a moment a minister, but after the establishment of the [[Second French Republic]], he was not re-elected deputy in the [[French National Assembly|National Assembly]].\n\nAfter the [[Franco-Prussian War]], he was returned to the [[Bordeaux]] assembly by his old ''[[D\u00e9partement in France|d\u00e9partement]]'' &mdash; [[Haute-Vienne]]. His [[Orl\u00e9anist]] tendencies and his objections to the [[Third French Republic|Third Republic]] were strong, and although he at first supported [[Adolphe Thiers]], he afterwards became a leader of the opposition to the [[President of the French Republic|president]]. He died, however, in 1873 at [[Morsang-sur-Seine]], before Theirs was actually driven from power.\n\n==Works==\nHis chief work is his ''Cours de litt\u00e9rature dramatique'' (1843\u20131863), a series of lectures better described by its second title ''De l'usage des passions dans le drame''. The author examined dramatic passions, discussing the mode in which they are treated in ancient and modern drama, poetry and romance. The book, a defence of the ancients against the moderns, \"did not\", according to the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition]]'', \"take into account the fact that only the best of ancient literature has come down to us.\" Girardin's ''oeuvre'' was, overall, very hostile toward [[Romanticism]].\n\nGirardin's other works included ''Essais de litt\u00e9rature'' (2 vols., 1844), made up chiefly of contributions to the ''D\u00e9bats'', his ''Notices sur l'Allemagne'' (1834), and many volumes of collected ''Souvenirs'', ''R\u00e9flexions'', etc., on foreign countries and passing events (including his notes on the [[Regulamentul Organic|period of Russian administration]] in the [[Danubian Principalities]]). His last major works were ''[[Jean de La Fontaine|La Fontaine]] et les Fabulistes'' (1867) and an ''\u00c9tude sur [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau|J.-J. Rousseau]]'' (1870) which had appeared in the ''[[Revue des deux mondes]]''.\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Saint-Marc Girardin|volume=24|page=29}} ''In turn, it cites as references:''\n**Flatzfield and Meunier, ''Les Critiques litt\u00e9raires du XIXe si\u00e8cle'' (1894)\n**Ch. Labitte, ''Saint-Marc Girardin'', in the ''Revue des deux mondes'' (Feb. 1845)\n**Tamisier, ''Saint-Marc Girardin; \u00e9tude litt\u00e9raire'' (1876)\n\n{{Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise Seat 23}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girardin, Marc}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:French historians]]\n[[Category:French literary critics]]\n[[Category:French memoirists]]\n[[Category:French people of the Revolutions of 1848]]\n[[Category:19th-century French politicians]]\n[[Category:French travel writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:19th-century French journalists]]\n[[Category:French male journalists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century historians]]\n[[Category:19th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century French male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Girardin"}
{"title_page": "Marc Boegner", "text_new": "'''Marc Boegner''', commonly known as '''''pasteur'' Boegner''' ({{IPA-fr|past\u0153\u0281 b\u0153\u0272e|lang}}; 21 February 1881 \u2013 18 December 1970), was a theologist, influential pastor, notable member of the [[French Resistance]], and a French essayist, and a notable voice in the [[ecumenical]] movement.\n\n==Biography==\n\nMarc Boegner was the nephew and disciple of the Lutheran pastor [[Tommy Fallot]], who founded [[Social Christianity]] in France.<ref>{{cite book|pages=46\u201347 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cMvCBD69TE8C&pg=PA46 |last1=Hill|first1=Christopher|last2=Monsarrat|first2=J.-P. |title=\"Appel\u00e9s \u00e0 t\u00e9moigner et \u00e0 servir\": l'affirmation commune de Reuilly : dialogue entre les \u00e9glises anglicanes de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande et les \u00e9glises luth\u00e9riennes et r\u00e9form\u00e9s de France |year=1999|publisher=Editions Olivetan|isbn=978-2-85304-147-8|chapter=Un panorama des relations entre l'\u00e9glise d'Angleterre et les \u00e9glises r\u00e9form\u00e9es en France}}</ref>\nBorn in [[\u00c9pinal]], [[Vosges (department)|Vosges]] in 1881, Boegner was educated in [[Orl\u00e9ans]], and later Paris, where he studied law. Poor eyesight was an obstacle to his pursuit of a career within the navy but after a spiritual conversion experience he entered the Faculty for Theology in Paris and in 1905 was ordained a pastor of the Reformed Church of France. After having been a Protestant [[pastor]] in a rural parish in Aouste-sur-Sye in [[Dr\u00f4me]], in 1911 he became professor of theology at the House of the Missions of Paris, and in 1918 went on to the Parish of Poissy-Annonciation where he remained until 1952. In 1928, he inaugurated the sermons of Protestant Lent on the radio, which contributed to his notoriety. There he preached on the [[oikoumene|unity of Christians]]. In 1929, he became the first president of the [[Protestant Federation of France]] (''F\u00e9d\u00e9ration protestante de France''), a position he held until 1961. In 1938 he became the first president of the national council of the [[Reformed Church of France]] (''l'\u00c9glise r\u00e9form\u00e9e de France''), a post he held until 1950. He was on two occasions the professor at the Academy of International Law at The Hague. Between 1938 and 1948 he was president of the administrative committee of the provisional [[World Council of Churches]] in formation. After the council had been formed he became one of its co-presidents, a post he held until 1954.\n\nBoegner actively worked, during the occupation, in an open way as well as clandestinely, to try to improve the lot of the Jews, and even defended and saved a number of them. His compassion extended also to many political refugees. He intervened with Pierre Laval, in vain, to ask him to give up including Jewish children younger than 16 years in the deportation convoys. In 1943, he condemned the forced sending of workers to [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] under the [[Service du travail obligatoire|STO]]. Against violence and the armed struggle, he let his faith and conscience choose against joining the [[Maquis (World War II)|Maquis]] in an early stage. His action to help the Jews during the war made him be awarded the [[Righteous among the Nations]] in [[Yad Vashem]] in 1988.\n\nHaving met six times, in the middle of his resistance work, Marshal [[Philippe P\u00e9tain]], he was decorated with the [[Order of the Francisque]] and was named a member of the National Council of [[Vichy France|Vichy]]. He remained, at the time of his questioning in the Allied lawsuit against the old leader, on 30 July 1945, to testify for the good intentions and the goodwill expressed by P\u00e9tain in the difficult circumstances of France - a lenient idea of P\u00e9tain's actions, today contradicted by authors and some historians.\n\nAfter the war, he continued his fight for unity while taking part in the [[ecumenism|ecumenical movement]] (''mouvement \u0153cum\u00e9nique''). He was also a Protestant observer during the [[Second Vatican Council]] (1962\u20131965) during which he staged a public dialogue with [[Augustin Bea|Cardinal Bea]] in Geneva. He also met [[Pope Paul V1]]. The ecumenical movement is the subject of his last book published in 1968 (''The Long Road to Unity'', Eng. trans. 1970).\n\nBoegner died in Paris.\n\n==Works==\n*''Les Cat\u00e9chismes de Calvin, \u00e9tude d'histoire et de cat\u00e9ch\u00e9tique'', th\u00e8se de doctorat soutenue devant la facult\u00e9 de th\u00e9ologie protestante en 1905\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1914)\n*''La Vie et la pens\u00e9e de T. Fallot'', 2 vol. (1914\u20131926)\n*''L'Influence de la R\u00e9forme sur le d\u00e9veloppement du droit international'' (1926)\n*''Le Christianisme et le monde moderne'' (1928, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''Les Missions protestantes et le droit international'' (1929)\n*''Dieu, l'\u00e9ternel tourment des hommes'' (1929, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''J\u00e9sus-Christ'' (1930, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''T. Fallot, l'homme et l'\u0153uvre'' (1931)\n*''Qu'est-ce que l'\u00c9glise ?'' (1931, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'\u00c9glise et les questions du temps pr\u00e9sent'' (1932)\n*''La Vie chr\u00e9tienne'' (1933)\n*''Le Christ devant la souffrance et devant la joie'' (1935, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'\u00c9vangile et le racisme'' (1939)\n*''Le Probl\u00e8me de l'unit\u00e9 chr\u00e9tienne'' (1947, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''La Pri\u00e8re de l'\u00c9glise universelle'' (1951)\n*''La Vie triomphante'' (1953)\n*''Le Chr\u00e9tien et la souffrance'' (1956)\n*''Les Sept paroles de la Croix'' (1957)\n*''Notre vocation \u00e0 la saintet\u00e9'' (1958)\n*''T\u00e9n\u00e8bres et Lumi\u00e8res aux abords du Calvaire'' (1960, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'Exigence \u0153cum\u00e9nique des \u00c9glises. Souvenirs et perspectives'' (1968)\n\n==Memberships and decorations==\n\n===Ecclesiastical===\n*President of the French Federation of Christian associations of students (1923\u20131935),\n*President of the Protestant Federation of France (1929\u20131961),\n*President of the national council of the reformed Church of France (1938\u20131950),\n*President of the Company of the evangelic missions of France (1945\u20131968),\n*President of the oecumenical Movement of the Christian Churches (1948\u20131954).\n\n===Other===\n*Member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques]] (1946)\n*Member of the ''Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise'' (1962). To date, Marc Boegner remains the only Pastor to ever be elected in the ''Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise''.\n*[[Righteous among the Nations]] (1988)\n*Grand Officer of the ''L\u00e9gion d'honneur''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Marc Boegner}}\n*[http://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/marc-boegner-1881-1970/ Detailed biography of Pastor Boegner in the Virtual Museum of Protestantism]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061124184913/http://www.academie-francaise.fr/immortels/base/academiciens/fiche.asp?param=624 Biographical note on the website of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]\n*[http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4042772 Marc Boegner] \u2013 his activity to save Jews' lives during the [[Holocaust]], at [[Yad Vashem]] website\n\n{{Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise Seat 2}}\n{{Holocaust France}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boegner, Marc}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from \u00c9pinal]]\n[[Category:French Calvinist and Reformed theologians]]\n[[Category:Calvinist pacifists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Lakanal alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Order of the Francisque recipients]]\n[[Category:French Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:20th-century Calvinist and Reformed theologians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Montparnasse Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century French theologians]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:Huguenots]]\n[[Category:20th-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:French Resistance members]]\n", "text_old": "'''Marc Boegner''', commonly known as '''''pasteur'' Boegner''' ({{IPA-fr|past\u0153\u0281 b\u0153\u0272e|lang}}; 21 February 1881 \u2013 18 December 1970), was a theologist, influential pastor, notable member of the [[French Resistance]], and a French essayist, and a notable voice in the [[ecumenical]] movement.\n\n==Biography==\n\nMarc Boegner was the nephew and disciple of the Lutheran pastor [[Tommy Fallot]], who founded [[Social Christianity]] in France.<ref>{{cite book|pages=46\u201347 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cMvCBD69TE8C&pg=PA46 |last1=Hill|first1=Christopher|last2=Monsarrat|first2=J.-P. |title=\"Appel\u00e9s \u00e0 t\u00e9moigner et \u00e0 servir\": l'affirmation commune de Reuilly : dialogue entre les \u00e9glises anglicanes de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande et les \u00e9glises luth\u00e9riennes et r\u00e9form\u00e9s de France |year=1999|publisher=Editions Olivetan|isbn=978-2-85304-147-8|chapter=Un panorama des relations entre l'\u00e9glise d'Angleterre et les \u00e9glises r\u00e9form\u00e9es en France}}</ref>\nBorn in [[\u00c9pinal]], [[Vosges (department)|Vosges]] in 1881, Boegner was educated in [[Orl\u00e9ans]], and later Paris, where he studied law. Poor eyesight was an obstacle to his pursuit of a career within the navy but after a spiritual conversion experience he entered the Faculty for Theology in Paris and in 1905 was ordained a pastor of the Reformed Church of France. After having been a Protestant [[pastor]] in a rural parish in Aouste-sur-Sye in [[Dr\u00f4me]], in 1911 he became professor of theology at the House of the Missions of Paris, and in 1918 went on to the Parish of Poissy-Annonciation where he remained until 1952. In 1928, he inaugurated the sermons of Protestant Lent on the radio, which contributed to his notoriety. There he preached on the [[oikoumene|unity of Christians]]. In 1929, he became the first president of the [[Protestant Federation of France]] (''F\u00e9d\u00e9ration protestante de France''), a position he held until 1961. In 1938 he became the first president of the national council of the [[Reformed Church of France]] (''l'\u00c9glise r\u00e9form\u00e9e de France''), a post he held until 1950. He was on two occasions the professor at the Academy of International Law at The Hague. Between 1938 and 1948 he was president of the administrative committee of the provisional [[World Council of Churches]] in formation. After the council had been formed he became one of its co-presidents, a post he held until 1954.\n\nBoegner actively worked, during the occupation, in an open way as well as clandestinely, to try to improve the lot of the Jews, and even defended and saved a number of them. His compassion extended also to many political refugees. He intervened with Pierre Laval, in vain, to ask him to give up including Jewish children younger than 16 years in the deportation convoys. In 1943, he condemned the forced sending of workers to [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] under the [[Service du travail obligatoire|STO]]. Against violence and the armed struggle, he let his faith and conscience choose against joining the [[Maquis (World War II)|Maquis]] in an early stage. His action to help the Jews during the war made him be awarded the [[Righteous among the Nations]] in [[Yad Vashem]] in 1988.\n\nHaving met six times, in the middle of his resistance work, Marshal [[Philippe P\u00e9tain]], he was decorated with the [[Order of the Francisque]] and was named a member of the National Council of [[Vichy France|Vichy]]. He remained, at the time of his questioning in the Allied lawsuit against the old leader, on 30 July 1945, to testify for the good intentions and the goodwill expressed by P\u00e9tain in the difficult circumstances of France - a lenient idea of P\u00e9tain's actions, today contradicted by authors and some historians.\n\nAfter the war, he continued his fight for unity while taking part in the [[ecumenism|ecumenical movement]] (''mouvement \u0153cum\u00e9nique''). He was also a Protestant observer during the [[Second Vatican Council]] (1962\u20131965) during which he staged a public dialogue with [[Augustin Bea|Cardinal Bea]] in Geneva. He also met [[Pope Paul V1]]. The ecumenical movement is the subject of his last book published in 1968 (''The Long Road to Unity'', Eng. trans. 1970).\n\nBoegner died in Paris.\n\n==Works==\n*''Les Cat\u00e9chismes de Calvin, \u00e9tude d'histoire et de cat\u00e9ch\u00e9tique'', th\u00e8se de doctorat soutenue devant la facult\u00e9 de th\u00e9ologie protestante en 1905\n*''The Unity of the Church'' (1914)\n*''La Vie et la pens\u00e9e de T. Fallot'', 2 vol. (1914\u20131926)\n*''L'Influence de la R\u00e9forme sur le d\u00e9veloppement du droit international'' (1926)\n*''Le Christianisme et le monde moderne'' (1928, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''Les Missions protestantes et le droit international'' (1929)\n*''Dieu, l'\u00e9ternel tourment des hommes'' (1929, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''J\u00e9sus-Christ'' (1930, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''T. Fallot, l'homme et l'\u0153uvre'' (1931)\n*''Qu'est-ce que l'\u00c9glise ?'' (1931, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'\u00c9glise et les questions du temps pr\u00e9sent'' (1932)\n*''La Vie chr\u00e9tienne'' (1933)\n*''Le Christ devant la souffrance et devant la joie'' (1935, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'\u00c9vangile et le racisme'' (1939)\n*''Le Probl\u00e8me de l'unit\u00e9 chr\u00e9tienne'' (1947, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''La Pri\u00e8re de l'\u00c9glise universelle'' (1951)\n*''La Vie triomphante'' (1953)\n*''Le Chr\u00e9tien et la souffrance'' (1956)\n*''Les Sept paroles de la Croix'' (1957)\n*''Notre vocation \u00e0 la saintet\u00e9'' (1958)\n*''T\u00e9n\u00e8bres et Lumi\u00e8res aux abords du Calvaire'' (1960, recueil de pr\u00e9dications)\n*''L'Exigence \u0153cum\u00e9nique des \u00c9glises. Souvenirs et perspectives'' (1968)\n\n==Memberships and decorations==\n\n===Ecclesiastical===\n*President of the French Federation of Christian associations of students (1923\u20131935),\n*President of the Protestant Federation of France (1929\u20131961),\n*President of the national council of the reformed Church of France (1938\u20131950),\n*President of the Company of the evangelic missions of France (1945\u20131968),\n*President of the oecumenical Movement of the Christian Churches (1948\u20131954).\n\n===Other===\n*Member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques]] (1946)\n*Member of the ''Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise'' (1962). To date, Marc Boegner remains the only Pastor to ever be elected in the ''Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise''.\n*[[Righteous among the Nations]] (1988)\n*Grand Officer of the ''L\u00e9gion d'honneur''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Marc Boegner}}\n*[http://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/marc-boegner-1881-1970/ Detailed biography of Pastor Boegner in the Virtual Museum of Protestantism]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061124184913/http://www.academie-francaise.fr/immortels/base/academiciens/fiche.asp?param=624 Biographical note on the website of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]\n*[http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4042772 Marc Boegner] \u2013 his activity to save Jews' lives during the [[Holocaust]], at [[Yad Vashem]] website\n\n{{Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise Seat 2}}\n{{Holocaust France}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boegner, Marc}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from \u00c9pinal]]\n[[Category:French Calvinist and Reformed theologians]]\n[[Category:Calvinist pacifists]]\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Lakanal alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Order of the Francisque recipients]]\n[[Category:French Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:20th-century Calvinist and Reformed theologians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Montparnasse Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century French theologians]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:Huguenots]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:French Resistance members]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Boegner"}
{"title_page": "L\u00e9on de Poncins", "text_new": "{{Infobox philosopher\n| name         = L\u00e9on de Poncins\n| image        = File:L\u00e9on de Poncins.jpg\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Gabriel L\u00e9on Marie Pierre de Montaigne de Poncins\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1897|11|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Civens]], [[Loire (department)|Loire]], [[France]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1975|12|18|1897|11|3|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Toulon]], France\n| occupation   = journalist, writer\n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = [[Julius Evola|Evola]], [[Barry Domvile|Domvile]], [[On\u00e9simo Redondo|Redondo]], [[The Britons]], [[Miguel Serrano|Serrano]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Serrano|first1=Miguel|authorlink1=Miguel Serrano|title=Adolf Hitler: The Ultimate Avatar|publisher=Ediciones la Nueva Edad|page=131|url=https://archive.org/stream/SerranoMiguelAdolfHitlerTheUltimateAvatar/Serrano_Miguel_-_Adolf_Hitler_The_Ultimate_Avatar_djvu.txt}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Viscount]] '''L\u00e9on de Poncins''' (3 November 1897 \u2013 18 December 1975) was a [[French people|French]] aristocrat and a [[traditional Catholic]] journalist and essayist. He authored numerous books and articles advancing a [[Judeo-Masonic conspiracy theory]].\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins' explanation for most of the major [[revolutionary movements|revolutionary political upheavals]] of [[modernity]] was the influence of certain [[secret societies]] with an [[anti-Christian]] agenda \u2014 as well as a \"occult war\" waged by those possessing a diabolical kind of \"faith\".\n\n==Biography==\nBorn Gabriel L\u00e9on Marie Pierre de Montaigne de Poncins in [[Civens]], [[Loire (department)|Loire]]. He was descended of an aristocratic family [[Ennoblement|ennobled]] in 1696.\n\nHis writings enjoyed some prominence in the 1930s (many of his works were translated into [[English language|English]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[German language|German]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]). L\u00e9on de Poncins contributed to many newspapers like ''[[Le Jour]]'', ''[[Le Figaro]]'', ''[[L'Ami du peuple]]'', and ''[[Le Nouvelliste (Valais)|Le Nouvelliste]]''; he also directed the journal ''[[Contre-R\u00e9volution]]'' (''Counter-Revolution'') from 1937 to 1939.\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins was a devout [[Catholic]] and [[counter-revolutionary]]. His writings show [[anti-Jewish]], [[anti-Communist]], [[Anti-Masonry|anti-Masonic]], and [[anti-progressive]] views. Until his death, in [[Toulon]], he denounced the occult forces and organizations that ruled the world and sought to poison Christianity.\n\n==Views==\n\n===Influence of secret societies===\nIn his writings, he denounced [[Masonic conspiracies]] (pointing out the relationship between [[History of Freemasonry in France#Revolution|Freemasonry and the French Revolution]], the [[League of Nations]], etc.), and the Jewish influence in Catholic affairs.\n\nHis work was seen as a continuation of the ''[[Revue Internationale des Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s Secr\u00e8tes]]'' ([''International Review of Secret Societies'']), whose primary editor was [[Mgr.]] [[Ernest Jouin]] (1844\u20131932).\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins was a friend of [[Emmanuel Malynski]] (died 1938)\u2014 with whom he wrote ''La Guerre occulte'' (''The Occult War'')<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rix|first1=Edouard|title=Emmanuel Malynski, m\u00e9taphysicien de la Guerre occulte|journal=R\u00e9fl\u00e9chir et Agir|date=Autumn 2004|issue=18|pages=48\u201349}}</ref>\u2014 and [[Jean Vaqui\u00e9]] (1911\u20131992), with whom he wrote in the journals ''Lectures fran\u00e7aises'' and ''Lecture et Tradition'', and for the [[Chir\u00e9-en-Montreuil]]-based publishing house [[\u00c9ditions de Chir\u00e9]]. L\u00e9on de Poncins wrote the preface to Vaqui\u00e9's ''La R\u00e9volution Liturgique'' ([''The Liturgical Revolution'']).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vaqui\u00e9|first1=Jean|title=La r\u00e9volution liturgique|date=1971|publisher=Diffusion de la Pens\u00e9e fran\u00e7aise|location=[[Chir\u00e9-en-Montreuil]]|url=http://www.a-c-r-f.com/documents/VAQUIE-Revolution_liturgique.pdf|accessdate=4 March 2016|language=French}}</ref>\n\n[[Julius Evola]] translated ''La Guerre occulte'' into [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Malinsky|first1=Emmanuel|author2=L\u00e9on de Poncins|title=La guerra occulta: armi e fasi dell'attacco ebraico-massonico alla tradizione europea|date=1939|publisher=U. Hoepli|location=[[Milan]]}}</ref> First published in 1939, with a preface written by Evola in his own name, the second edition in 1961 had a new introduction, signed \"Koussis\", and an unsigned conclusion (both revealed posthumously to be by Evola).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evola|first1=Julius|author2=(translated by Bruno Cariou)|authorlink1=Julius Evola|title=L\u00e9on de Poncins\u2019 ''The Occult War''|url=http://www.counter-currents.com/2013/01/leon-de-poncins-the-occult-war/|website=Counter-Currents|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1949 letter from [[Ren\u00e9 Guenon]] to Evola, he expresses a belief that L\u00e9on de Poncins was subjected to attacks from \"a group of dangerous [[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerers]]\" who were connected to his secretary, Eve Louguet.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guenon|first1=Ren\u00e9|author2=Cologero|title=Letters from Guenon to Evola (IX)|url=http://www.gornahoor.net/?p=4662|website=[[Gornahoor Press]]|accessdate=6 March 2016|date=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===On World War I===\nIn his historical analysis of the [[First World War]], L\u00e9on de Poncins suggests that concerted [[lobbying]] by international [[Zionist]] circles led to the creation of the future [[Jewish state]] in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] by means of manipulating alliances and oppositions between countries. In 1916\u2014 at a time when [[Germany]] triumphed on all fronts and the [[United Kingdom|British]] planned to sign an [[armistice]] then advanced by [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|the Kaiser]]\u2014 Zionists secured a promise of Palestine (then under the domination of the [[Ottoman Empire]]) as a Jewish settlement  from the government of [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in exchange for the [[United States]]' entry into the war alongside the [[Triple Entente]]. To corroborate his thesis, L\u00e9on de Poncins cited ''Great Britain, The Jews and Palestine'', a 1936 book by pro-Zionist author, [[Samuel Landman]].\n\n===On Vatican II===\nDuring the [[Second Vatican Council]], following the vote on 20 November 1964, at the third session of the provisional scheme dealing with [[Relations between Catholicism and Judaism|the Church's attitude towards Judaism]], L\u00e9on de Poncins wrote a pamphlet, ''Le Probl\u00e8me juif face au Concile'' ([''The Jewish Question Facing the Council'']),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Held|first1=George F.|title=L\u00e9on de Poncins: The Problem with the Jews at the Council, Part I|url=http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/07/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-i/|website=[[The Occidental Observer]]|accessdate=2 March 2016|date=23 July 2013}} [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/07/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-ii/ Part II], [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-iii/ Part III], and [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/20262/ Part IV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307113027/http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/20262/ |date=2016-03-07 }}</ref> which was distributed to the [[bishops]] before the fourth and final session. The author noted \"by the Council Fathers a profound misunderstanding of what constitutes the essence of Judaism.\" L\u00e9on de Poncins' advice had a significant effect on the drafting of ''[[Nostra aetate]]'', adopted on 28 October 1965.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laurigan|first1=Michel|title=Vatican II : Du \" mythe de la substitution \" \u00e0 la religion noachide|journal=Sel de la terre|date=Autumn 2003|issue=46|url=http://www.nostra-aetate.org/Bibliotheque/2003-10_SDT_Michel-LAURIGAN_Vatican%20II_Du-Mythe-de-la-substitution-a-la-religion-noachide_12p.pdf|accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Translated title !! Publishing notes !! ISBN\n|-\n| 1929 || ''Les Forces secr\u00e8tes de la R\u00e9volution'' || ''The Secret Powers Behind Revolution: Freemasonry and Judaism'' || Bossard. Second revised and expanded edition, 1929. Boswell (London; English translation), 1929. Reprinted by Christian Book Club of America ([[Hawthorne, CA]]), 1969, 1980, 1988, and 1996.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Poncins|first1=L\u00e9on de|title=Freemasonry & Judaism: The Secret Powers Behind Revolution|date=1996|orig-year=1986|publisher=Omni/Christian Book Club|location=Palmdale, CA|url=https://archive.org/stream/FreemasonryAndJudaism/freemasonry-and-judaism|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref> Bloomfield Books ([[Sudbury, Suffolk]]),  1989. Published as ''Freemasonry & Judaism: Secret Powers Behind Revolution'' by A & B Books Publishers (Brooklyn, NY), 1994. Reprinted by \u00c9ditions Saint-Remi, 2005. || {{ISBN|2845194870}}\n|-\n| 1931 || ''Refus\u00e9 par la presse'' || [''Rejected by the Press''] || \u00c9ditions de la Revue fran\u00e7aise. Reprinted by \u00c9ditions Saint-Remi || {{ISBN|2845194307}}\n|-\n| 1932 || ''La Franc-ma\u00e7onnerie, puissance occulte'' || [''Freemasonry: Secret Power''] || Bossard. Reprinted by \u00c9ditions Saint-Remi, 2005 || {{ISBN|2845194986}}\n|-\n| 1932 || ''Les Juifs, ma\u00eetres du monde'' || [''The Jews: Masters of the World''] || Bossard. Reprinted by \u00c9ditions Saint-Remi, 2005 || {{ISBN|2845194854}}\n|-\n| 1934 || ''Temp\u00eate sur le monde, ou La Faillite du progr\u00e8s'' || [''Storm on the World, or the Bankruptcy of Progress''] || Beauchesne. Reprinted by \u00c9ditions Saint-Remi, 2005 || {{ISBN|284519482X}}\n|-\n| 1934 || ''La Dictature des puissances occultes, La F