count]] '''L\u00e9on de Poncins''' (3 November 1897 \u2013 18 December 1975) was a [[French people|French]] aristocrat and a [[traditional Catholic]] journalist and essayist. He authored numerous books and articles advancing a [[Judeo-Masonic conspiracy theory]].\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins' explanation for most of the major [[revolutionary movements|revolutionary political upheavals]] of [[modernity]] was the influence of certain [[secret societies]] with an [[anti-Christian]] agenda \u2014 as well as a \"occult war\" waged by those possessing a diabolical kind of \"faith\".\n\n==Biography==\nBorn Gabriel L\u00e9on Marie Pierre de Montaigne de Poncins in [[Civens]], [[Loire (department)|Loire]]. He was descended of an aristocratic family [[Ennoblement|ennobled]] in 1696.\n\nHis writings enjoyed some prominence in the 1930s (many of his works were translated into [[English language|English]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[German language|German]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]). L\u00e9on de Poncins contributed to many newspapers like ''[[Le Jour]]'', ''[[Le Figaro]]'', ''[[L'Ami du peuple]]'', and ''[[Le Nouvelliste (Valais)|Le Nouvelliste]]''; he also directed the journal ''[[Contre-R\u00e9volution]]'' (''Counter-Revolution'') from 1937 to 1939.\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins was a devout [[Catholic]] and [[counter-revolutionary]]. His writings show [[anti-Jewish]], [[anti-Communist]], [[Anti-Masonry|anti-Masonic]], and [[anti-progressive]] views. Until his death, in [[Toulon]], he denounced the occult forces and organizations that ruled the world and sought to poison Christianity.\n\n==Views==\n\n===Influence of secret societies===\nIn his writings, he denounced [[Masonic conspiracies]] (pointing out the relationship between [[History of Freemasonry in France#Revolution|Freemasonry and the French Revolution]], the [[League of Nations]], etc.), and the Jewish influence in Catholic affairs.\n\nHis work was seen as a continuation of the ''[[Revue Internationale des Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s Secr\u00e8tes]]'' ([''International Review of Secret Societies'']), whose primary editor was [[Mgr.]] [[Ernest Jouin]] (1844\u20131932).\n\nL\u00e9on de Poncins was a friend of [[Emmanuel Malynski]] (died 1938)\u2014 with whom he wrote ''La Guerre occulte'' (''The Occult War'')<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rix|first1=Edouard|title=Emmanuel Malynski, m\u00e9taphysicien de la Guerre occulte|journal=R\u00e9fl\u00e9chir et Agir|date=Autumn 2004|issue=18|pages=48\u201349}}</ref>\u2014 and [[Jean Vaqui\u00e9]] (1911\u20131992), with whom he wrote in the journals ''Lectures fran\u00e7aises'' and ''Lecture et Tradition'', and for the [[Chir\u00e9-en-Montreuil]]-based publishing house [[\u00c9ditions de Chir\u00e9]]. L\u00e9on de Poncins wrote the preface to Vaqui\u00e9's ''La R\u00e9volution Liturgique'' ([''The Liturgical Revolution'']).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vaqui\u00e9|first1=Jean|title=La r\u00e9volution liturgique|date=1971|publisher=Diffusion de la Pens\u00e9e fran\u00e7aise|location=[[Chir\u00e9-en-Montreuil]]|url=http://www.a-c-r-f.com/documents/VAQUIE-Revolution_liturgique.pdf|accessdate=4 March 2016|language=French}}</ref>\n\n[[Julius Evola]] translated ''La Guerre occulte'' into [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Malinsky|first1=Emmanuel|author2=L\u00e9on de Poncins|title=La guerra occulta: armi e fasi dell'attacco ebraico-massonico alla tradizione europea|date=1939|publisher=U. Hoepli|location=[[Milan]]}}</ref> First published in 1939, with a preface written by Evola in his own name, the second edition in 1961 had a new introduction, signed \"Koussis\", and an unsigned conclusion (both revealed posthumously to be by Evola).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evola|first1=Julius|author2=(translated by Bruno Cariou)|authorlink1=Julius Evola|title=L\u00e9on de Poncins\u2019 ''The Occult War''|url=http://www.counter-currents.com/2013/01/leon-de-poncins-the-occult-war/|website=Counter-Currents|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1949 letter from [[Ren\u00e9 Guenon]] to Evola, he expresses a belief that L\u00e9on de Poncins was subjected to attacks from \"a group of dangerous [[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerers]]\" who were connected to his secretary, Eve Louguet.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guenon|first1=Ren\u00e9|author2=Cologero|title=Letters from Guenon to Evola (IX)|url=http://www.gornahoor.net/?p=4662|website=[[Gornahoor Press]]|accessdate=6 March 2016|date=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===On World War I===\nIn his historical analysis of the [[First World War]], L\u00e9on de Poncins suggests that concerted [[lobbying]] by international [[Zionist]] circles led to the creation of the future [[Jewish state]] in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] by means of manipulating alliances and oppositions between countries. In 1916\u2014 at a time when [[Germany]] triumphed on all fronts and the [[United Kingdom|British]] planned to sign an [[armistice]] then advanced by [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|the Kaiser]]\u2014 Zionists secured a promise of Palestine (then under the domination of the [[Ottoman Empire]]) as a Jewish settlement  from the government of [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in exchange for the [[United States]]' entry into the war alongside the [[Triple Entente]]. To corroborate his thesis, L\u00e9on de Poncins cited ''Great Britain, The Jews and Palestine'', a 1936 book by pro-Zionist author, [[Samuel Landman]].\n\n===On Vatican II===\nDuring the [[Second Vatican Council]], following the vote on 20 November 1964, at the third session of the provisional scheme dealing with [[Relations between Catholicism and Judaism|the Church's attitude towards Judaism]], L\u00e9on de Poncins wrote a pamphlet, ''Le Probl\u00e8me juif face au Concile'' ([''The Jewish Question Facing the Council'']),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Held|first1=George F.|title=L\u00e9on de Poncins: The Problem with the Jews at the Council, Part I|url=http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/07/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-i/|website=[[The Occidental Observer]]|accessdate=2 March 2016|date=23 July 2013}} [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/07/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-ii/ Part II], [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/leon-de-poncins-the-problem-with-the-jews-at-the-council-part-iii/ Part III], and [http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/20262/ Part IV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307113027/http://www.theoccidentalobserver.net/2013/08/20262/ |date=2016-03-07 }}</ref> which was distributed to the [[bishops]] before the fourth and final session. The author noted \"by the Council Fathers a profound misunderstanding of what constitutes the essence of Judaism.\" L\u00e9on de Poncins' advice had a significant effect on the drafting of ''[[Nostra aetate]]'', adopted on 28 October 1965.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laurigan|first1=Michel|title=Vatican II : Du \" mythe de la substitution \" \u00e0 la religion noachide|journal=Sel de la terre|date=Autumn 2003|issue=46|url=http://www.nostra-aetate.org/Bibliotheque/2003-10_SDT_Michel-LAURIGAN_Vatican%20II_Du-Mythe-de-la-substitution-a-la-religion-noachide_12p.pdf|accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Translated title !! Publishing notes !! ISBN\n|-\n| 1929 || ''Les Forces secr\u00e8tes de la R\u00e9volution'' || ''The Secret Powers Behind Revolution: Freemasonry and Judaism'' || Bossard. Second revised and expanded edition, 1929. Boswell (London; English translation), 1929. Reprinted by Christian Book Club of America ([[Hawthorne, CA]]), 1969, 1980, 1988, and 1996.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Poncins|first1=L\u00e9on de|title=Freemasonry & Judaism: The Secret Powers Behind Revolution|date=1996|orig-year=1986|publisher=Omni/Christian Book Club|location=Palmdale, CA|url=https://archive.org/stream/FreemasonryAndJudaism/freemasonry-and-judaism|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref> Bloomfield Books ([[Sudbury, Suffolk]]),  1989. Published as ''Freema