Aix]]. He held the post barely a year, resigning it to become a leader-writer on the ''Journal des d\u00e9bats''. He also wrote in the ''Courrier du dimanche'', and for a very short time in the ''Presse''.\n\nHis chief works are ''Essais de politique et de litt\u00e9rature'' (three series, 1859\u20131866), and ''Essais sur les moralistes fran\u00e7ais'' (1864). He was, however, rather a journalist than a writer of books, and was one of the chief opponents of the empire on the side of moderate [[liberalism]]. He underwent the usual difficulties of a journalist under that regime, and was once imprisoned. In 1865 he was elected to the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]].\n\n[[August Strindberg]] referred to him in his novel ''The Growth of a Soul'': {{quote|Now he took to reading again. Chance brought into his hand two of \"the best books which one can read.\" They were De Tocqueville's ''[[Democracy in America]]'' and Pr\u00e9vost-Paradol's ''[[The New France]]''. The former increased his doubts as to the possibility of democracy in an uncultivated community. Written with sincere admiration for the political institutions of America, which the author holds up as a pattern for Europe, this work points out so sincerely the dangers of democracy, as to make even a born hater of the aristocracy pause.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/44107/44107-h/44107-h.htm#CHAPTER_I August Strindberg, ''The Growth of a Soul'']</ref>}}\n\n==Opposition and death==\nThe accession of [[\u00c9mile Ollivier]] to power was fatal to Pr\u00e9vost-Paradol, who apparently believed in the possibility of a liberal empire, and consequently accepted the appointment of envoy to the [[United States]]. This was the signal for the most unmeasured attacks on him from the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He had scarcely installed himself in his post before the outbreak of the [[Franco-Prussian War]] occurred. He shot himself at [[Washington, DC|Washington]] on 19 July 1870, and later died.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Pr\u00e9vost-Paradol, Lucien Anatole}}\n{{Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise Seat 37}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Lucien-Anatole Pr\u00e9vost-Paradol |sopt=w}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prevost-Paradol, Lucien Anatole}}\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Diplomats who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:French male writers who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:1829 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France to the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century French journalists]]\n[[Category:French male journalists]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n[[Category:French people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century essayists]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien-Anatole_Pr%C3%A9vost-Paradol"}
{"title_page": "Tina Dixon", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, actress and comedian}}\n'''Tina Dixon''' was an American R&B singer, actress and comedian. She became a featured singer in [[Swing music|swing]] bandleader [[Jimmie Lunceford]]'s band early in her career and recorded for [[Excelsior Records|Excelsior]], [[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]], and [[King Records (United States)|King Records]] in the 1940s. By the 1970s, Dixon was making x-rated party records as '''Auntie Tina Dixon'''.\n\n== Life and career ==\nBorn in [[Detroit]], Dixon began her singing career at the age of 18. Her first gig was at the Club Ballyhoo in Detroit and eventually she performed at the [[Apollo Theater]] in Harlem. In 1939, Dixon married tap dancer Leon Collins in Detroit. In 1942, they moved to New York City where Dixon was billed to perform with the [[Jimmie Lunceford]] orchestra. Dixon helped land her husband a spot in the show when the opening act called out sick, resulting in a five-year contract for Collins.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hill|first=Constance Valis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_HERDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA176&dq=tina+dixon+blues+singer&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1ud2Ug-znAhW9knIEHbvrCJ0Q6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=tina%20dixon%20blues%20singer&f=false|title=Tap Dancing America: A Cultural History|date=|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-19-022538-4|location=|pages=176|language=en}}</ref> They with his band at theaters and nightclubs. She appeared at the Tic Toc Club in [[Boston]]; Cafe Zanzibar in New York; Club Bali in Washington, D.C.. Dixon was managed by Harold F. Oxley [who also managed Jimmie Lunceford and [[Mabel Scott]]]. Dixon also appeared on television, made color movie shorts for Pathe, and performed at army and navy camps.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Band Profiles - The Billboard 1944 Music Year Book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/40s/1944/BB-1944-YB.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=253|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1945, Dixon recorded \"E-Bob-O-Le-Bob\" with Jimmie Lunceford for [[Armed Forces Radio Service]] (AFRS) [[Jubilee (radio program)|Jubilee]]. AFRS recordings were made by African-American artists to showcase their music to the [[United States Armed Forces]] and allied nations; they weren't meant for commercial release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colorado.edu/amrc/glenn-miller-archive/gma-catalogs/jubilee|title=AFRS Jubilee|last=|first=|date=|website=American Music Research Center|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Dixon is credited as the songwriter for the record, but shortly after, singer [[Helen Humes]] released the song under the title \"Be-Baba-Leba\" ([[Aladdin Records|Philo]] 106).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 26, 1946|title=Barnet Granted Pub Rights to \"Be-Baba\"|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/40s/1946/BB-1946-01-26.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=16|via=}}</ref> Humes is credited as the songwriter on her record which became a hit single although Dixon had been performing it on her act since 1942. Later in 1945, Dixon recorded \"E-Bob-O-Le-Bob\" with the Flennoy Trio.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 10, 1945|title=Record Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YxgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT81&dq=Flennoy+Trio+E-Bob-O-Le-Bob+tina+dixon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjspcCmr-znAhWLY98KHbamDZ4Q6AEwAnoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=Flennoy%20Trio%20E-Bob-O-Le-Bob%20tina%20dixon&f=false|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=78|via=}}</ref> The copyright controversy was noted in ''Billboard'' (January 26, 1946), when Humes' version was hot on the chart:<blockquote>[[Charlie Barnet]] has secured exclusive publishing rights for his Indigo pub outfit to the swing novelty tune.... Barnet closed deal for ''Be-Baba-Leba'' with Harold Oxley, the agent, who controlled original copyright of the tune introduced in the first place by Tina Dixon, whom Oxley manages. Dixon also made recording of tune for Excelsior label. Her side, however, came out after the Humes version for Philo. Barnet dickered with Helen Humes on tune for a while until he learned that her recorded version followed Dixon's featuring of the song in night clubs, therefore making Dixon's a prior copyright.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>Dixon never achieved chart success, but she continued performing and befriending other entertainers, including comedian [[Redd Foxx]]. In 1975, she appeared on his hit television series ''[[Sanford and Son|Sanford & Son]].'' By then she was known as Auntie Tina Dixon and she released two raunchy comedy albums, ''Take It Out Of This!'' and ''Calling All Freaks'' on [[Laff Records]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 15, 1979|title=Who Will Succeed Moms Mabley As Top X-Rated Comedienne?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SkIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=tina+dixon+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf64Hr0uznAhVnj3IEHaqgCvkQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=tina%20dixon%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=60|via=}}</ref> Dixon had a role in the 1977 film [[Big Time (1977 film)|''Big Time'']]. \n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n*1945: The Flennoy Trio \u2013 \"E-Bob-O-Le-Bob\" ([[Excelsior Records|Excelsior]] 130)\n*1947: Tina Dixon & Lady Blue Allstar \u2013 \"Don't You Know I Want To Love You\" / \"Hello Baby\" ([[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]] 205)\n*1949: Tina Dixon And Gene Nero Sextet \u2013 \"Walk That Walk, Daddy-O\" / \"Parrot Bar Boogie\" ([[King Records (United States)|King]] 4257)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 22, 1949|title=Record Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_B8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=King+4257+PARROT+BAR+BOOGIE&source=bl&ots=esERDijJrs&sig=ACfU3U1dHZ1lVr9hzdMcHNN_gLkyqYSnEQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimhPfyz-znAhVHknIEHZC8A6sQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=King%204257%20PARROT%20BAR%20BOOGIE&f=false|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=52|via=}}</ref>\n*1950: Tina Dixon And Gene Nero Sextet \u2013 \"Blow Mr. Be-Bop\" (King 4332)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 28, 1950|title=Record Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=Gene+Nero+Sextet+/+Tina+Dixon+And+Gene+Nero+Sextet+%E2%80%8E%E2%80%93+Blow+Mr.+Be-Bop+/+What+I+Say&source=bl&ots=N7x1C-OBf6&sig=ACfU3U1xxntQBx15cM8hXfnKYwTbpvOckQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6mY35ruznAhUFZN8KHbM6AnoQ6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Gene%20Nero%20Sextet%20%2F%20Tina%20Dixon%20And%20Gene%20Nero%20Sextet%20%E2%80%8E%E2%80%93%20Blow%20Mr.%20Be-Bop%20%2F%20What%20I%20Say&f=false|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=108|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''Take It Out Of This!'' ([[Laff Records]])\n* ''Calling All Freaks'' (Laff Records)\n\n=== Album appearances ===\n\n* 1985: ''Those Great Blues Girls From The 40's'' ([[Capitol Records]])\n* 2002: ''Fine Fine Baby: King's Queens \u2013 King's Blues Gals Of The '40s'' ([[Westside Records]])\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.uncamarvy.com/ReBop/rebop.html Hey! Ba-Ba-Re-Bop] on Marv Goldberg's R&B Notebooks\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1707318/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_t7 Tina Dixon] on [[IMDb]]\n\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Detroit]]\n[[Category:African-American comedians]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Aladdin Records artists]]\n[[Category:King Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, actress and comedian}}\n'''Tina Dixon''' was an American R&B singer, actress and comedian. She became a featured singer in [[Swing music|swing]] bandleader [[Jimmie Lunceford]]'s band early in her career and recorded for [[Excelsior Records|Excelsior]], [[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]], and [[King Records (United States)|King Records]] in the 1940s. By the 1970s, Dixon was making x-rated party records as '''Auntie Tina Dixon'''.\n\n== Life and career ==\nBorn in [[Detroit]], Dixon began her singing career at the age of 18. Her first gig was at the Club Ballyhoo in Detroit and eventually she performed at the [[Apollo Theater]] in Harlem. In 1939, Dixon married tap dancer Leon Collins in Detroit. In 1942, they moved to New York City where Dixon was billed to perform with the [[Jimmie Lunceford]] orchestra. Dixon helped land her husband a spot in the show when the opening act called out sick, resulting in a five-year contract for Collins.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hill|first=Constance Valis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_HERDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA176&dq=tina+dixon+blues+singer&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1ud2Ug-znAhW9knIEHbvrCJ0Q6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=tina%20dixon%20blues%20singer&f=false|title=Tap Dancing America: A Cultural History|date=|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-19-022538-4|location=|pages=176|language=en}}</ref> They with his band at theaters and nightclubs. She appeared at the Tic Toc Club in [[Boston]]; Cafe Zanzibar in New York; Club Bali in Washington, D.C.. Dixon was managed by Harold F. Oxley [who also managed Jimmie Lunceford and [[Mabel Scott]]]. Dixon also appeared on television, made color movie shorts for Pathe, and performed at army and navy camps.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Band Profiles - The Billboard 1944 Music Year Book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/40s/1944/BB-1944-YB.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=253|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1945, Dixon recorded \"E-Bob-O-Le-Bob\" with Jimmie Lunceford for [[Armed Forces Radio Service]] (AFRS) [[Jubilee (radio program)|Jubilee]]. AFRS recordings were made by African-American artists to showcase their music to the [[United States Arme