erefore making Dixon's a prior copyright.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>Dixon never achieved chart success, but she continued performing and befriending other entertainers, including comedian [[Redd Foxx]]. In 1975, she appeared on his hit television series ''[[Sanford and Son|Sanford & Son]].'' By then she was known as Auntie Tina Dixon and she released two raunchy comedy albums, ''Take It Out Of This!'' and ''Calling All Freaks'' on [[Laff Records]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 15, 1979|title=Who Will Succeed Moms Mabley As Top X-Rated Comedienne?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SkIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=tina+dixon+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf64Hr0uznAhVnj3IEHaqgCvkQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=tina%20dixon%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=60|via=}}</ref> Dixon had a role in the 1977 film [[Big Time (1977 film)|''Big Time'']]. \n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n*1945: The Flennoy Trio \u2013 \"E-Bob-O-Le-Bob\" ([[Excelsior Records|Excelsior]] 130)\n*1947: Tina Dixon & Lady Blue Allstar \u2013 \"Don't You Know I Want To Love You\" / \"Hello Baby\" ([[Aladdin Records|Aladdin]] 205)\n*1949: Tina Dixon And Gene Nero Sextet \u2013 \"Walk That Walk, Daddy-O\" / \"Parrot Bar Boogie\" ([[King Records (United States)|King]] 4257)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 22, 1949|title=Record Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_B8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=King+4257+PARROT+BAR+BOOGIE&source=bl&ots=esERDijJrs&sig=ACfU3U1dHZ1lVr9hzdMcHNN_gLkyqYSnEQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimhPfyz-znAhVHknIEHZC8A6sQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=King%204257%20PARROT%20BAR%20BOOGIE&f=false|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=52|via=}}</ref>\n*1950: Tina Dixon And Gene Nero Sextet \u2013 \"Blow Mr. Be-Bop\" (King 4332)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 28, 1950|title=Record Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=Gene+Nero+Sextet+/+Tina+Dixon+And+Gene+Nero+Sextet+%E2%80%8E%E2%80%93+Blow+Mr.+Be-Bop+/+What+I+Say&source=bl&ots=N7x1C-OBf6&sig=ACfU3U1xxntQBx15cM8hXfnKYwTbpvOckQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6mY35ruznAhUFZN8KHbM6AnoQ6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Gene%20Nero%20Sextet%20%2F%20Tina%20Dixon%20And%20Gene%20Nero%20Sextet%20%E2%80%8E%E2%80%93%20Blow%20Mr.%20Be-Bop%20%2F%20What%20I%20Say&f=false|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=108|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''Take It Out Of This!'' ([[Laff Records]])\n* ''Calling All Freaks'' (Laff Records)\n\n=== Album appearances ===\n\n* 1985: ''Those Great Blues Girls From The 40's'' ([[Capitol Records]])\n* 2002: ''Fine Fine Baby: King's Queens \u2013 King's Blues Gals Of The '40s'' ([[Westside Records]])\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.uncamarvy.com/ReBop/rebop.html Hey! Ba-Ba-Re-Bop] on Marv Goldberg's R&B Notebooks\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1707318/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_t7 Tina Dixon] on [[IMDb]]\n\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Detroit]]\n[[Category:African-American comedians]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Aladdin Records artists]]\n[[Category:King Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:American female jazz singerstoCategory:American jazz singersusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tina_Dixon"}
{"title_page": "Lucien Rebatet", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name    =Lucien Rebatet\n| other_names =\n| image    =Rebatet librairie.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption   =\n|birth_date       = 15 November 1903\n|birth_place      = [[Moras-en-Valloire]], France\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|1972|08|24|1903|11|15}}\n|death_place      = Moras-en-Valloire, France\n| death_cause =\n| known    =\n| occupation = journalist, author\n| religion  =\n| spouse   =\n| partner   =\n| children  =\n| relations  =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n}}\n\n{{French literature sidebar}}\n\n'''Lucien Rebatet''' (15 November 1903 \u2013 24 August 1972) was a French author, journalist, and intellectual. He is known as an exponent of [[fascism]] and virulent [[antisemitism|antisemite]] but also as the author of ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'', regarded by some as one of the greatest novels of the post-war era.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nRebatet was born and died in [[Moras-en-Valloire]], [[Dr\u00f4me]].  As a young man, Rebatet was educated in [[Saint-Chamond, Loire]]. From 1923 to 1927 he studied at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], after which he became an insurance agent. It was only in 1929 that he began his career as a writer, becoming a music and film critic (the latter under the pseudonym '''Fran\u00e7ois Vinneuil''') for the [[far right]] [[Integralism|integralist]] ''[[Action Fran\u00e7aise]]'' newspaper. In 1932 Rebatet became a contributor to the right-wing newspaper ''[[Je suis partout]]'', for which he wrote until the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] liberation in 1944. In 1938 he became head of information for Action Fran\u00e7aise and worked closely with the movement's founder, [[Charles Maurras]].\n\nLong before the outbreak of war between France and [[Nazi Germany]], Rebatet expressed sympathy for [[Nazism|National Socialism]], notably in his articles for ''Je suis partout'' (\"I Am Everywhere\"), in which he accused [[Jews]] of fomenting a war to topple [[Adolf Hitler]]\u2019s r\u00e9gime. In 1940 he was drafted into the [[French Army]] and, although he served, openly hoped for a \"''short and disastrous war for France''\".\n\n===Collaboration===\nAfter the [[fall of France]] he became a radio reporter for the [[Vichy France|Vichy government]]. He soon left this post, as well as Action Fran\u00e7aise, to join [[Jacques Doriot]]'s newspaper ''[[Cri Du Peuple]]'', and to continue his writings for ''Je suis partout''.\n\nIn 1942 Rebatet published a lengthy [[pamphlet]] entitled ''[[Les D\u00e9combres]]'' (\"The Ruins\"), in which he traced the forces he believed to have led France to its fall. He firmly accused [[Third French Republic|Third Republic]] politicians and its military leadership, as well as French Jews - who he claimed were the prime cause of France's political and military woes. ''Les D\u00e9combres'' is the clearest expression of Rebatet's fascism, as well as his most virulently antisemitic work. The same year, he began writing ''[[Les Deux \u00e9tendards]]'' (\"The Two Standards\"), his first novel.\n\nIn August 1944 Rebatet fled France for Germany, travelling to the [[Sigmaringen enclave]] (place of refuge for Vichy authorities as well as the more famous French writer, [[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line|C\u00e9line]]). It was in Sigmaringen that Rebatet completed ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'', which would be published in 1952 by [[Gallimard]]. He was arrested in Austria in 1945.\n\n===After the war===\nRebatet was sent back to France and, in 1946, received a [[death sentence]], which was commuted to [[Penal labour|forced labor]] the next year. Released from prison in 1952, he returned to journalism in 1953, becoming the director of the literary section of ''[[Dimanche Matin]]''. In 1954, Gallimard published Rebatet's second novel, ''[[Les Epis M\u00fbrs]]'' (\"The Ripe Grains\"). His final work was a history of music which he began writing in 1965, and which was published by [[Laffont]] in 1969.\n\nAlthough Rebatet continued to proclaim his adherence to fascism until his death, his antisemitism became less pronounced after the war{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}, showing even admiration for the state of Israel.<ref>http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/07/28/01002-20140728ARTFIG00036--l-extreme-droite-etait-pro-israelienne-jusqu-a-la-guerre-du-kippour.php</ref>\n\nDespite his controversial biography, there are those, such as [[George Steiner]], who claim that Lucien Rebatet was a great writer, and that ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'' in particular deserves to be considered an important novel in French literary history.\n\n==Cultural references==\n*Rebatet is depicted in [[Jonathan Littell]]'s [[historical novel]] ''[[Les Bienveillantes]]'', where he is a friend of the main character Maximilian Aue.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rebatet, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dr\u00f4me]]\n[[Category:French art critics]]\n[[Category:French collaborators with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:French fascists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:French literary critics]]\n[[Category:French political writers]]\n[[Category:People affiliated with Action Fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:French military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:French anti-communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:French male novelists]]\n[[Category:French prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by France]]\n[[Category:20th-century French essayists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name    =Lucien Rebatet\n| other_names =\n| image    =Rebatet librairie.jpg\n| image_size  = 225px\n| caption   =\n|birth_date       = 15 November 1903\n|birth_place      = [[Moras-en-Valloire]], France\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|1972|08|24|1903|11|15}}\n|death_place      = Moras-en-Valloire, France\n| death_cause =\n| known    =\n| occupation = journalist, author\n| religion  =\n| spouse   =\n| partner   =\n| children  =\n| relations  =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n}}\n\n{{French literature sidebar}}\n\n'''Lucien Rebatet''' (15 November 1903 \u2013 24 August 1972) was a French author, journalist, and intellectual. He is known as an exponent of [[fascism]] and virulent [[antisemitism|antisemite]] but also as the author of ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'', regarded by some as one of the greatest novels of the post-war era.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nRebatet was born and died in [[Moras-en-Valloire]], [[Dr\u00f4me]].  As a young man, Rebatet was educated in [[Saint-Chamond, Loire]]. From 1923 to 1927 he studied at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], after which he became an insurance agent. It was only in 1929 that he began his career as a writer, becoming a music and film critic (the latter under the pseudonym '''Fran\u00e7ois Vinneuil''') for the [[far right]] [[Integralism|integralist]] ''[[Action Fran\u00e7aise]]'' newspaper. In 1932 Rebatet became a contributor to the right-wing newspaper ''[[Je suis partout]]'', for which he wrote until the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] liberation in 1944. In 1938 he became head of information for Action Fran\u00e7aise and worked closely with the movement's founder, [[Charles Maurras]].\n\nLong before the outbreak of war between France and [[Nazi Germany]], Rebatet expressed sympathy for [[Nazism|National Socialism]], notably in his articles for ''Je suis partout'' (\"I Am Everywhere\"), in which he accused [[Jews]] of fomenting a war to topple [[Adolf Hitler]]\u2019s r\u00e9gime. In 1940 he was drafted into the [[French Army]] and, although he served, openly hoped for a \"''short and disastrous war for France''\".\n\n===Collaboration===\nAfter the [[fall of France]] he became a radio reporter for the [[Vichy France|Vichy government]]. He soon left this post, as well as Action Fran\u00e7aise, to join [[Jacques Doriot]]'s newspaper ''[[Cri Du Peuple]]'', and to continue his writings for ''Je suis partout''.\n\nIn 1942 Rebatet published a lengthy [[pamphlet]] entitled ''[[Les D\u00e9combres]]'' (\"The Ruins\"), in which he traced the forces he believed to have led France to its fall. He firmly accused [[Third French Republic|Third Republic]] politicians and its military leadership, as well as French Jews - who he claimed were the prime cause of France's political and military woes. ''Les D\u00e9combres'' is the clearest expression of Rebatet's fascism, as well as his most virulently antisemitic work. The same year, he began writing ''[[Les Deux \u00e9tendards]]'' (\"The Two Standards\"), his first novel.\n\nIn August 1944 Rebatet fled France for Germany, travelling to the [[Sigmaringen enclave]] (place of refuge for Vichy authorities as well as the more famous French writer, [[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line|C\u00e9line]]). It was in Sigmaringen that Rebatet completed ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'', which would be published in 1952 by [[Gallimard]]. He was arrested in Austria in 1945.\n\n===After the war===\nRebatet was sent back to France and, in 1946, received a [[death sentence]], which was commuted to [[Penal labour|forced labor]] the next year. Released from prison in 1952, he returned to journalism in 1953, becoming the director of the literary section of ''[[Dimanche Matin]]''. In 1954, Gallimard published Rebatet's second novel, ''[[Les Epis M\u00fbrs]]'' (\"The Ripe Grains\"). His final work was a history of music which he began writing in 1965, and which was published by [[Laffont]] in 1969.\n\nAlthough Rebatet continued to proclaim his adherence to fascism until his death, his antisemitism became less pronounced after the war{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}, showing even admiration for the state of Israel.<ref>http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/07/28/01002-20140728ARTFIG00036--l-extreme-droite-etait-pro-israelienne-jusqu-a-la-guerre-du-kippour.php</ref>\n\nDespite his controversial biography, there are those, such as [[George Steiner]], who claim that Lucien Rebatet was a great writer, and that ''Les Deux \u00e9tendards'' in particular deserves to be considered an important novel in French literary history.\n\n==Cultural references==\n*Rebatet is depicted in [[Jonathan Littell]]'s [[historical novel]] ''[[Les Bienveillantes]]'', where he is a friend of the main character Maximilian Aue.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rebatet, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dr\u00f4me]]\n[[Category:French art critics]]\n[[Category:French collaborators with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:French essayists]]\n[[Category:French fascists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:French literary critics]]\n[[Category:French political writers]]\n[[Category:People affiliated with Action Fran\u00e7aise]]\n[[Category:French military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:French anti-communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:French male novelists]]\n[[Category:French prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by France]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Rebatet"}
